text:
i love the inspirational quote cards. yet, i‚Äôve heard from women who have expressed that reading them can sometimes cause fear and dread - how can they do this? is it possible? how do you move from the reality to the idea of your dream? how do you go from the nike slogan ‚Äújust do it‚Äù to figuring out how to do it?

these are all very real and valid questions.  that is what i do as a coach.  i help you get out of your head (which is often filled with self-doubt and negative thoughts telling you can‚Äôt do it), set goals that are possible, develop a plan, and work with you on your journey to reaching your goals.

are you ready for a really cool transformational journey where your dreams can become your reality?  or, maybe you are wanting to care for yourself better and figure out how to like yourself (and love yourself!). if part of you is saying ‚Äúlet‚Äôs do this‚Äù, connect with me by clicking on the link in my bio ‚ñ∂Ô∏è @denisestyer and we can discuss how.  looking forward to it! üíú

text:
i came to gems after being arrested at the age of 22. i was living with my pimp and his children, and didn‚Äôt see a future for myself. i didn‚Äôt want to engage in groups with other members, but i kept coming back to talk to staff. it was the first time anyone had ever pointed out that i had strengths. i realized i wanted to be a chef. i moved into a transitional living program and then got kicked out. it was hard for me to follow rules. i began studying for my ged and passed my test. i reapplied for the housing program and they gave me a second chance. i completed a culinary arts program with the help of gems‚Äô educational initiative program and spoke at their graduation. i eventually reconnected with family and am living in virginia with them while working at a restaurant. i definitely see a vision for my future now; i‚Äôm living it!
.
.
.

text:
the first rule of femme cabal book club: talk about femme cabal book club.

the second rule of femme cabal book club: tell your friends about femme cabal book club.

femme cabal presents our very first book club event on february 26th, 2019 at the barking buffalo cafe.

our first book is the water cure, ‚Äúa fiercely poetic feminist revenge fantasy about three sisters raised on an isolated island to fear men.‚Äù margaret atwood calls the book, ‚Äúa gripping, sinister fable!‚Äù ooooh, spooky.

we will discuss the book and its themes, and how those themes relate to feminism in edmonton in 2019. but, let's be honest here: this is just for fun. we won't get too scholarly about it.

what do you need to do to join femme cabal book club? 
#1: read the book. 
#2: rsvp by sending us a message letting us know that you would like to join. space is limited, so we will start a waitlist if too many people show interest.
#3: show up at the barking buffalo cafe at 7 pm on tuesday, february 26th.

bring wine if you desire. we will have snacks and the cafe will be open for purchase of coffee drinks. 
tell your friends! space is limited, so rsvp asap! you snooze, you lose! early bird gets the worm, etc etc. 
everyone is welcome.

text: to anyone out there suffering from sexual assault, domestic violence or physical abuse, you are non-deserving, you are beautiful, you are smart, and you are full of everything that is good! i was assaulted over 5 years ago by someone i was dating at the time. because of my assault, i have developed an auto immune disease, ptsd and increased depression and anxiety. it is an awful thing that has happened, however, it has helped me change the world. i am extremely grateful to the young woman that reached out to me who shared the same assaulter. without her strength and kindness i would‚Äôve never been able to report him to the police. she is now a close and dear friend of mine and because of her, i have pushed myself to advocate and help fellow survivors. the powers of goodness in this world and outside ours want you to be safe, happy and living a healthy wonderful life! you are not alone! since i have begun advocating i have spoken to men, women, old, young, straight, gay, all races, all ethnicities... everyone is affected by this. i am not a professional, only a survivor set on advocating and finding solutions. if you are looking for professional help please reach out to the heartly house, mental health association of frederick county, frederick memorial hospital, frederick county sheriff's office, md, rainn or maryland coalition against sexual assault (mcasa). over the span of my healing journey, i have used all of these resources and have had great experiences with these professionals. please reach out if you need to talk or if you need a helping hand pointing you in the right direction for professional help. getting help is not easy... talking about assault is one of the hardest things you can do. but you can do it! now is the time to help yourself. never forget how loved, how special and how wonderful you are. i love you and you are loved by all the good powers of this universe. ‚ù§Ô∏è @rainn  @heartlyhouse  @mha_frederick  @frederickcountysheriff #enddomesticviolence #endsexualviolence #advocate #metoo #reachout #goodvibesonly #positivity #movingforward #validation #endrapeculture #changetheworld #besafe #bekind #healing #selfhelp #youarenotalone #webelieveinyou #

tool by @denise.wakeman on view now in enough: me too exhibition. see the dynamic video in full at the reception next friday 1/25 - join us!

artist's statement: "tool is an exploration of power dynamics, the body, and gender norms. tools cast in silicone and rendered to resemble genitalia play with the associations that tools have to masculinity and the phallus. the feminine hands that manipulate these objects serve to highlight the objects‚Äô impotence, vulnerability, and their capacity to inflict pain. the act of manipulation situates the hands in a position of power further complicating masculinity‚Äôs association with inherent capability and power." #metoo #mcaexhibition #enough

text:
interview with barbara @_ohlivia__ ‚û°Ô∏è‚û°Ô∏è‚û°Ô∏èswipe to watch the video

this project is about women, their bodies and their opinion about the fashion industry/social media.
it is focusing on small interviews with many different women, from different sociocultural backgrounds, talking about their bodies and the negative impact on social media in their lives.
through this research project, i came to the conclusion that women are very self-conscious about their physical appearance and what others will think about the way they look.
as a stylist, i want to understand which kind of imagery i can produce in the future, to make women feel better with themselves?!?
3 main questions:
how do you feel about your body?
social media affects your life?
what should change in the fashion industry in the future?

text:
black girls and women face greater threats to their safety than whites, including not only domestic violence and sexual assault, but also violence by law enforcement, educators, and the court system. in the face media attention for surviving r kelly and cyntoia brown's case, we encourage all of our followers to find ways to center and stand with black women and girls - because the examples lifted up in the media right now are not anomalies, but all-too-common experiences for women and girls of color across the united states. we cannot make progress in the work to end violence against women and girls if we do not address the unique experiences that women and girls of color face each day.

text:
interview with maddy
@maddstemple @maddy_temple ‚û°Ô∏è‚û°Ô∏è‚û°Ô∏èswipe to watch the video

this project is about women, their bodies and their opinion about the fashion industry/social media.
it is focusing on small interviews with many different women, from different sociocultural backgrounds, talking about their bodies and the negative impact on social media in their lives.
through this research project, i came to the conclusion that women are very self-conscious about their physical appearance and what others will think about the way they look.
as a stylist, i want to understand which kind of imagery i can produce in the future, to make women feel better with themselves?!?
3 main questions:
how do you feel about your body?
social media affects your life?
what should change in the fashion industry in the future?

text:
mystikal could be walking out of jail as early as next week if everything goes to plan. according to a report from tmz today (jan. 13), a combination of funds from friends and a new record deal could lead to his release from caddo correctional center. the release would come before his trial for first degree rape and second-degree kidnapping starts this spring.

the rapper's attorney, joel pearce, told the celebrity news outlet that his client's friends and family have been raising money for his $3 million bond, but it was a newly-signed record deal that really helped him reach his goal. according to tim yazbeck, another lawyer for the embattled rhymer, his new deal consists of him recording three unreleased albums. he's hoping to get an advance within days. mystikal's legal team is confident that the rapper can post bail and be released by the end of next week.

the ghetto fabulous artist has been behind bars since august 2017, after an unnamed woman accused both him and another man, averweone darnell holman, of raping her in may 2017. the alleged rape took place in october 2016. holman faces the same charges. a third person, a woman named tenichia monieck wafford, has also been charged with obstruction of justice in relation to the alleged assault for reportedly trying to persuade the woman to recant her story.

mystikal, whose real name is michael tyler, has denied all rape allegations against him. his lawyer believes the entire situation was fueled by the #metoo movement, which has exposed sexual misconduct by male executives and celebrities in the film and music industry.

mystikal‚Äôs rape trial is expected to start in may.

text:
üî¨ #metoo in stem: role of organized labor. .
the seattle chapter of 500 women scientists presents a discussion and workshop focusing on organized labor in stem fields and highlighting the impact of the #metoo movement on stem professionals. speakers include leaders from local labor organizations that represent stem workers, as well as people on the front lines of developing greater protections for women in stem, who experience rates of workplace sexual harassment second only to those in the military. the session provides guidance on how to navigate workplace conflicts, and attendees will leave with a toolkit of strategies for dealing with gendered harassment in the workplace.
.

text:
- what we worked on was ... data harvesting programs where we would pull data from users of apps and all of their friend networks and run that data through algorithms that could profile their personality traits and other psychological attributes, wylie told cnn‚Äôs don lemon monday evening.

wylie said the ultimate goal was to obtain information in order to exploit mental vulnerabilities that our algorithms showed that [facebook users] had.

in addition to wylie and cambridge analytica, accounts of cambridge analytica‚Äôs parent company, strategic communication laboratories, and those of a university of cambridge psychologist aleksandr kogan were also suspended.

the accounts were suspended because facebook received reports that data that had been shared with cambridge and wylie from kogan‚Äôs app may not have been completely deleted. kogan‚Äôs app was removed in 2015 and facebook said they had been previously provided certifications that the data had been deleted. - several days ago, we received reports that, contrary to the certifications we were given, not all data was deleted, facebook said friday. - we are moving aggressively to determine the accuracy of these claims. if true, this is another unacceptable violation of trust and the commitments they made. we are suspending scl/cambridge analytica, wylie and kogan from facebook, pending further information.

special counsel robert mueller asked cambridge analytica last fall to surrender emails from any of its employees who worked for the trump campaign, the wall street journal reported in december. the firm complied to the request.

diana stancy correll
washington examiner

text: i don't understand that someone can kill someone else/ i don't understand hate/ i don't understand that a lot of people take the way they are living in as granted/ i don't understand that you can put money before nature/ i don't understand that in a democracy you elect people who have to work with people with completely different view so they both can rule/ i don't understand how a hug could hurt someone/ i don't understand why men are still earning more than women for the same job/ i don't understand people who are going each day to their work which they hate, but who refuse to change from job or to learn something new for a job they love/ i don't understand people to who you admit your error(s), but who remain silent/ i don't understand the coldness in this society without a gentle human touch and warmth/ i don't understand discrimination due to gender, religion, skin color/ i don't understand how caring words could harm someone/ i don't understand how cruel people can be, not only to someone else, but especially to themselves/ i don't understand ... and so on. i have or had a lot of questions. a part of me wanted an answer on every question. of course it is impossible. meanwhile i understand that it is even pointless; it is a never-ending story. for each answer you will receive more unanswered questions. the solution is to look at all those questions. to observe how you feel about them. when needed to forgive them. and finally to release them. also this is a lesson in non-attachment on the journey of pure oneness... #insight #wisdom #truelove #unconditionallove #inspiration #choice #understanding #knowledge #ascension #nirvana #enlightment #evolution #awareness #awakening #wayofliving #wayofthinking #nojudgement #lifestyle #lotus #light #nonattachment #nogrievances #innerpeace #metoo #purenondualism #pureoneness #acim

this project is about women, their bodies and their opinion about the fashion industry/social media.
it is focusing on small interviews with many different women, from different sociocultural backgrounds, talking about their bodies and the negative impact on social media in their lives.
through this research project, i came to the conclusion that women are very self-conscious about their physical appearance and what others will think about the way they look.
as a stylist, i want to understand which kind of imagery i can produce in the future, to make women feel better with themselves?!?
3 main questions:
how do you feel about your body?
social media affects your life?
what should change in the fashion industry in the future?
.

text:
#thisisamerica
#thirdüëÅdigitalkings 
seventy years ago in groveland, fla., a white teenager named norma padgett accused four black men of kidnapping and raping her in a car on a dark road.

two of the men would eventually be shot dead by the segregationist sheriff of lake county and his angry mob, and the other two wrongfully convicted on little evidence. the case of the groveland four, as they became known, inspired a pulitzer prize-winning book and has been considered for decades one of florida‚Äôs most grave injustices and a symbol of racism in the jim crow south.

in 2017, the state of florida¬†formally apologized for what happened in the summer of 1949. and on friday, the state‚Äôs clemency board voted to posthumously pardon all four men: ernest thomas, samuel shepherd, charles greenlee and walter irvin.

the deciding factor, the board said, was not whether padgett lied ‚Äî as the relatives of the accused insisted she‚Äôd done ‚Äî but whether the men ever had a chance at a fair trial. padgett, now 86, watched from her wheelchair as newly inaugurated gov. ron desantis (r) declared that they had not. he called the case a ‚Äúmiscarriage of justice" and said that the ‚Äúappropriate thing to do is grant pardons.‚Äù .
.
.

text:
#imtherocketman

you can see in my face that i was an active mind.¬† a bit mischievous, but it was due to my adventurous and creative soul.¬† however, this is the face of an lgbtq kid that grew up in the bahamas as a pastor's kid where he always heard of hell, fire and damnation.¬† additionally, it's technically "legal" to discriminate or kill lgbtq persons and have their cases "swept under a rug" as there are no laws protecting its own citizens in the constitution.¬† these same citizen help to build the nation through providing jobs, paying taxes and much more; they even help to pay the salaries of the police officers who sometimes do not protect lgbtq persons.¬† furthermore, i've felt the rejection by some family members due to being different or for having "gay tendencies". this forced me as a kid to create other worlds where i can be "accepted". ultimately, the difficult circumstances expanded my creative consciousness; on the other hand, facades and lies where built to protect myself from the discrimination or torture i've watched other lgbtq family and strangers went through.¬† the energy it takes to create and maintain a facade/lies/dishonesty for almost 30 years of my life became toxic, and i eventually opened up to family before the age of 30. they gave a calum scott's response and said we love you #nomatterwhat .  then i moved to canada as a refugee claimant seeking protection from my home country.  now due to canada's love and support, i'm now able to open up to talk about it because somewhere out there is another little lgbtq boy or girl who are living in constant fear as did i!¬† i want them to know that it's okay, and to find love within themselves while surrounding themselves with those who truly love them.¬† love and light will guide you down the right path!

#klevarsmith #loveandlight #lgbtq #idontgiveafuckanymore #loveyourself #loveothers #lovegod #wearespecial #metoo #ilovecanada #ibleedredandwhite
name: K. Levar Smith

text:
love letter monday: breaking cycles, breaking news

this photo was taken a month after my ex-husband and i separated. it was while i was inside that toxic marriage that i began to write. essay upon essay‚Äîchapters, perhaps‚Äîsent by my inner voice to warn me, protect me, wizen me. to let me know that contrary to his words, i did have value. that contrary to the world‚Äôs wounds, i did deserve kindness and respect. that contrary to the narrative of systemic racism and sexism that i had been born into, i had the power to author a new story. for myself. my family. my future children.

i‚Äôm thrilled to share that today, january 14, 2019, the north clackamas school district received an innovation grant from the oregon department of education to adopt i am yours into their english language arts curriculum. i am yours will be used as the common reading for high school juniors and seniors to engage in critical conversations about diversity, marginalization, social justice, racism, sexism, opportunity gap, privilege, breaking free and healing from trauma, the #metoo movement and our path forward, and how to use the power of their voices as agents of positive change, courage, and love in the world. the curriculum will be put into action in the 2019-2020 school year throughout oregon.

to you, who may be inside your moment of uncertainty, pain, or loss: have faith. you were born to experience and voice a specific story. traverse the valleys and falls of your life, pay attention to the wisdom mined from your wounds. everything can be used to inform and enrich your service to others. it will make sense. if not in the valley of pain, then one day, months, years later.

the thing that got me through that marriage was the audacious conviction that there was no way he was my story. i kept telling myself, i was born for a destiny so much bigger than the cramped quarters of a toxic home.

you and your voice matter. you were born for greatness and you embody tremendous resilience, by virtue of being human. voice your anthem. i am listening.

love, reema
‚Ä¢

‚Ä¢
(image of reema jumping with joy, against a white backdrop.)
‚Ä¢

text:
#validationfromuk #uksongwritingcontest2018 #countrymusic

on my bday in dec 2018, the results came in... this is no easy feat... the uk has a 1.4 billion dollar music industry; furthermore, the uk has been in the music business for centuries even before the us and canada were even countries!¬† thus, they have heard and seen it all before.¬† also, they are historical in exporting legendary acts, even legendary lgbtq acts such as david bowie, freddie mercury, and sir elton john.¬† currently, they are still exporting iconic lgbtq acts such as sam smith and calum scott to name a few!¬† i say this to say that you have to bring something unique and of a high standard to the table when we are considering placement in the uk!¬† this being my first country song, out of many more to come, to place this high shows the natural creative instincts that reside in me.¬† this also comes after giving such a personal story of the abuse i've faced told differently!
.
also to place against writers from all over the world including professional writers in nashville, who are paid to write country hits/albums daily, makes it that much more meaningful.  only the top 1-2% of songs in the competition make it this far... country isnt an easy genre to compose as a good country song requires a dynamic story!¬† thus, this song is a template for the others to follow, and with my new expanded creative consciousness, even greater is on the horizon.

#klevarsmith #paragonicentertainment #loveandlight #insecuritymetoo #metoo #uksongwritingcontest #2018 #thebestisyettocome #countrymusic #growth #selfloveandacceptance

text:
r. kelly revealed...#muterkelly .
.
marsha moment message.  like many of you - @pink_chanty and i watched @lifetimetv ‚Äúsurviving r. kelly‚Äù depicting kelly‚Äôs sadistic behaviors inflicted on young, innocent women from all walks of life and we have both listened to the backlash against r. kelly, the comments of those remaining loyal to him and r. kelly‚Äôs numerous responses to the charges levied against him by those he had abused. well....
.
here is just one phrase i would like to use to describe how i  felt and feel and what my heart is experiencing:  r. kelly is a malicious, vile, sadistic and despicable human being!! .
.
a little harsh for marshahugs to say - i don‚Äôt think so...!!.
.
my name is marsha r. bonner - i have a wife and four children with one being a young female who is 13 years old.  this type of  manipulative, domineering behavior goes to my core...for real!!.
.
like many of you, yes - i listened, sang, danced to and applauded his musical creative genius - yes, he is a talented man. however, i never explored or questioned his character, ethics or integrity.  to be honest, i was not that interested in his life, as i was doing my best to live my own.  and, i allowed his music to define for me the kind of man i thought he was. #fact #truth #blind.
.
well, now that the truth has been revealed about this particular celebrity, let‚Äôs challenge ourselves to be more thoughtful and deliberate of who we praise with high esteem and regard and allow ourselves to dig just a little deeper to confirm that they actually deserve the praise bestowed on them by us.
.
come on now...let‚Äôs all stop letting celebrity status define who a person really is - what we see and hear ain‚Äôt always what it really is. but, hey - you already knew this - right??...let‚Äôs roll. marshahugs aka marsha r. bonner.
.

since i started working this past fall, i have found it difficult to fit in everything i need to do for not only my mental & spiritual health, but my physical health as well.  between meetings, church, book work, bible journaling, pd time, keeping up on the household chores, homework with the girls, after school activities, having to work from home at night most days, trying to squeeze in a workout here & there had started to seem an impossible task as of late.
‚Ä¢
there just isn‚Äôt enough time in the day bc as someone with not only a chronic pain condition, but narcolepsy as well, i need to make sure i get adequate sleep to function & not be in as much pain or feeling like i‚Äôm ready to pass out all day. the catch, i need to workout to keep those illnesses from crippling me too.
‚Ä¢
this new program i started today has made that possible again!  it‚Äôs only 20min a day, man i felt every single minute of it!! i can‚Äôt wait to see the transformation after these next 6wks.
‚Ä¢
#faithhopelove #teamburninitdown #20minuteworkout #feltgood #transform20

text:
quiet as a mouse ii
30‚Äùx40‚Äù

the good ol‚Äô boys club just wants women to be quiet, don‚Äôt speak up, don‚Äôt have a voice, don‚Äôt have independent thought and definitely don‚Äôt be in a power position. they want to keep you tied up and quiet. 
speak up. unite. demand equality. 
do not be silent! roar. 
arguably a top 5 indelible image and first cartoon character of our childhood years. 
minnie will never be the same. 
a mere part of a larger series of artworks that were to be, and are, my commentary on where it seems our country, society and culture is today compared to when i was a child. 
the crux of the series is based on childhood cartoons and characters that i had grown up with and that represent my childhood. now, these characters are distorted into something that will never, at least unlikely, be the same again. they used to be sharp, clean lines and brightly colored.... now they are rough, dirty, twisted and in black and white. 
i hope you like it. it is also a bit of therapy for me realizing a dealing with the state of our country right now.

tell rca records: drop r. kelly now!
rally to protect black girls
wednesday, january 16th
9am - 10am | rca & sony headquarters | 25 madison ave.

join with our allies, black women's blueprint, girls for gender equity, color of change, credo, and ultraviolet to protest rca‚Äôs continued support of sexual predator r. kelly and their silence and complicity in his long history of abuse of young black girls. 
lifetime's docuseries surviving r. kelly, is an undeniable investigation into r. kelly's decades of sexual abuse perpetrated on young black women and girls and those in the music industry who have not only enabled him, but profited from him. it's long overdue that his survivors are finally being heard. despite years of public outcry and advocacy to #muterkelly and hearing from the young black women and their families who have stepped forward to say #metoo, rca records has remained silent.

it's past time for rca records and their parent company, sony, to drop r. kelly now. 
please rsvp on facebook and share the event widely!

what: protest rca records: drop r. kelly now and protect black girls
when: wednesday, january 16th at 9:00 am 
where: rca records & sony hq: 25 madison ave. (@ 25th st.) ny, ny 10010
across from madison square park on the east side of the park 
don't forget to share and sign color of change's petition to drop r. kelly now.

text:
interview with maria
‚û°Ô∏è‚û°Ô∏è‚û°Ô∏èswipe to watch the video

this project is about women, their bodies and their opinion about the fashion industry/social media.
it is focusing on small interviews with many different women, from different sociocultural backgrounds, talking about their bodies and the negative impact on social media in their lives.
through this research project, i came to the conclusion that women are very self-conscious about their physical appearance and what others will think about the way they look.
as a stylist, i want to understand which kind of imagery i can produce in the future, to make women feel better with themselves?!?
3 main questions:
how do you feel about your body?
social media affects your life?
what should change in the fashion industry in the future?
.

text:
speaking of music...and as i peruse profiles should share others‚Äô talent too if i can find the time!

for the singers out there, this talent @nixo_official_ is an example of what i feel is the emotional connection many singers want to inhabit for the audience to just want more...wow, he has a crazy cool voice and it is the passion that delivers for me!‚Ä¶in one of his other clips at the troy bar, allows his voice to enter into, what i call the prince arena of wild abandmonment, while maintaining the musicality to reign in the emotional drive lifting the voice...i hope he is just scratching the surface because i feel he is amazing as a talent...hope some or all of you dig it too!  i spent 12 years in instrumental music, so could read music, understand theory to a degree and grew up with my mom and dad singing at the piano and singing jazz classics etc...so i wanted to add i hope that gives my opinion some traction since i am often asked to manage folks in different areas and find many musicians profiles compelling that share their work...and kick myself for not singing when i was twenty...as stage fright developed soon after, though with modeling i could be seen without the vulnerability singing creates for an artist...but find it exciting to see how much talent is out there as life unfolds...an aaaaamazing amount! wow! üòä

text: in preparation for this saturday‚Äôs women‚Äôs march, we will be doing a swip wow countdown, each day highlighting a female activist! we begin with no one other than tarana burke, the women behind the #metoo movement. ms burke spent her life working tirelessly to uplift and unite victims of sexual assault in a common struggle and with a hope to expose this form of oppression yet also its disturbing normalcy in contemporary society. in 2007, ms burke created just be inc., a nonprofit for these victims which provided resources previously inaccessible to those in need. simultaneously she started a movement titled, me too, words she believe represented not only the pain and pattern of sexual assault but more importantly, solidarity. in 2017 actress alyssa milano tweeted these words in response to that month‚Äôs harvey weinstein allegations and out rose a twitter movement. she later credited ms burke and her role in this movement two days later. ms burke has been a beacon of hope for thousands of women by creating a movement of unity, strength and healing. her work and significance has at times been overshadowed and ignored, yet her power present a need for intersectionality in the feminist movement. she has engraved her name in history as a feminist, woman of color, and revolutionary.
name: Stanford Women in Politics

text: i saw this play call ‚Äúhear word‚Äù on saturday. all nigerian casts, well played out, great talentsüôèüèæ. the story line was a true reminder of what women go through in their entire lifetime. being second class rated and not valued for what they are worth. it touches every aspects of the #metoo movement and more, to include sex trafficking, abusive relationships, child marriages, monsters in laws, etc. the second part of the play was more empowering, tells that with a greater platform, our voices are stronger than we ever thought possible. #hearword is highly recommended to everyone. for men, to know what your daughters go through in the hands of some horrible men/women. for women, to be a great supporter of one another. for mothers, let us be open-minded to make our daughters feel comfortable enough to come to us with their problems. we must believe them, we must support them and we should fight the cause for them and with them‚ù§Ô∏è

text:
i was so excited to read this and am so happy i did. 
warning: spoilers below

the book started slow for me. circe was born from the sun god and a nymph and not looked upon very highly by any of her kind. at the beginning of the story, she was honestly kind of pathetic, laying at her father‚Äôs feet, desperate for any attention. so meek and quivering all the time. it isn‚Äôt until she falls in love with a mortal that she begins to grow as a person (or goddess so to speak) and the story picks up speed. 
this book was dubbed as the original #metoo story so i was braced and waiting. the incident happens well into the book, but is also another turning point for circe. by the end of the book circe went from an unlikable character who i felt no connection with to an admirable, strong character who i felt a sisterhood with. she struggled through so many of the same battles i have and while she faltered at times, she retained her goodness. circe is an epic adventure told from the woman‚Äôs point of view, and how mightily does that change the timbre of the story. rather an evil witch who tempts men to her island so she can turn them into beasts, circe is a trapped goddess and witch who in the aftermath of a traumatic rape, turns men who come to her island with ill intent into the pigs that she feels they truly are. part in protection, but yes, also part in vengeance and wrath. she had decided she would never be a victim again. and she never is. ‚Äúcirce‚Äù is a story about trauma, growth, finding out who you truly are, and seeing the story from the woman‚Äôs perspective. how i cheered when circe was trying to get stuff done with a baby and then toddler and how impossible it was. truth, sister! and all written beautifully and with vivid descriptions that left my mind dazzling in gold and sulfur and silver. 
#circe #bookreview #womansperpective #unreadshelfproject2019 #januarybook #check #bookstagram
name: Mai Wen

#
google employees participate in a walkout to protest how the tech giant handled sexual misconduct in mountain view, california, on nov. 1, 2018. the mass walkout was sparked by a recent¬†new york times report¬†that claimed google gave¬†millions of dollars to some executives in secret exit packages after they were accused of sexual misconduct. photo: michael short/bloomberg recent shareholder lawsuits against google parent company alphabet inc. mark the latest of a new approach in tackling sexual harassment allegations in the #metoo era. the¬†lawsuits, both filed in san mateo superior court in california, accuse alphabet¬†board members of breaching¬†their fiduciary duty¬†by covering up a lengthy pattern of gender discrimination and sexual harassment perpetrated by google executives. such activity, the derivative suits allege, had adverse impact on company profits and ability to hire and retain top talent and also exposed it to lawsuits and regulatory action. ‚Äúthe board knowingly participated in or acquiesced to conduct by the company‚Äôs senior executives that caused the company to violate various laws,‚Äù said one of the suits, filed by attorneys at berman tabacco and¬†cohen milstein sellers & toll. ‚Äúdefendants‚Äô conduct has already cost the company hundreds of millions of dollars in generous exit packages to wrongdoers and exposed‚Ä¶

text:
appealing for donations for a worthy cause, especially if you care about fighting systemic racism and access for all to mental health care. 
harriet‚Äôs dream has been established by prominent american activist & author, catrice jackson, to provide desperately needed mental health care to black women in the us. (please swipe above for detailed info on the mental illness epidemic that is killing black women & also the need for safe spaces for these women.)
the deadline for stage 2 of this project is fast approaching & any amount you can offer will help. people who donate $200usd or more can email catrice (details above) to receive a t-shirt featuring the beautiful logo for harriet‚Äôs dream. something you can wear proudly in support of this cause.
as a suffer of severe mental illness throughout my entire life, i can say with confidence i would be dead without the high quality care & support i‚Äôve received. in saying that, i have also been on the receiving end of prejudice & dismissive attitudes from doctors & therapists due to my being a young female. i was often treated poorly or ignored because it was assumed i wasn‚Äôt astute enough to know my own mind or know when something was wrong. fortunately, as a white woman, i had access to plenty of good people who did see and hear me, & did what they could to keep me going. i have also had access to many spaces where i have felt safe enough to focus on my healing. this is not the case for woc, who are seen & heard even less by the people who are supposed to help them.
i am painfully aware that my privilege as a white woman has given me much better odds at survival than any woc. this is wrong. throughout my treatment i‚Äôve often thought of the high mortality rate in australia‚Äôs indigenous population due to mental illness. now i am also aware of the same issues amongst black americans. black women in particular are expected to support everyone (including ww) around them, neglecting themselves in the process. this is a very important project that will do so much good.
please note, if you are aware of a similar service for indigenous australians please let me know. 
link in my bio to harriet‚Äôs dream. 
thank you

how much of what we hear being preached in the name of jesus is but the regurgitations and ramblings of people who can only repeat what everyone else is saying? where is the revelation of jesus christ? there are many echoes in the land, but few voices. voices are formed in the wilderness, not on a stage or upon a pulpit in a church building. john the baptist, moses, paul, joseph, they all found a voice and a message in the wilderness.

text:
#30haribercerita 2019 spesial 30 tahun tragedi junko furuta.
15 - internet, dan faktor pemicu kekerasan seksual

kekerasan seksual saat ini tidak mengenal waktu dan tempat, pelaku bisa saja melancarkan aksinya di ruang umum sekalipun. temuan¬†safety audit¬†un women, ada beberapa hal yang menjadi faktor pemicu terjadinya kekerasan maupun pelecehan seksual di jakarta. 
pertama adalah soal infrastruktur dan transportasi publik yang kurang memadai. misalnya, tidak adanya penerangan yang cukup di jalan atau gang, trotoar yang tidak memadai, tidak adanya cctv di tempat strategis, hingga transportasi publik yang kurang aman. "bayangan dan ketakutan akan terjadinya kekerasan dan pelecehan seksual, sering kali membatasi akses dan ruang gerak perempuan dan anak di ruang publik kota," ucap sabine machl, un women representative indonesia di dalam acara peringatan hari anti kekerasan terhadap perempuan di jakarta, sabtu (25/11/2017). faktor kedua adalah perilaku dan norma sosial. hal ini mencakup kekerasan diterima secara budaya, prilaku kekerasan dianggap suatu yang lazim dan dapat diterima secara sosial, kurangnya respons dari penonton yang menyaksikan tindakan kekerasan.

ketiga dikarenakan pengalaman kekerasan yaitu pernah menyaksikan kekerasan atau mengalami sebelumnya saat kanak-kanak.

sementara faktor keempat, korban pelecehan seksual kerap disalahkan, misalnya dari cara berpakaiannya. pandangan yang salah ini malah menyudutkan korban pelecehan seksual.

sabine mengatakan, fasilitas publik harus dibenahi agar para perempuan aman dan nyaman beraktivitas. (berlanjut di komentar)

text:
a few months later, in autumn 2013, wylie met steve bannon. at the time, he was editor-in-chief of breitbart, which he had brought to britain to support his friend nigel farage in his mission to take britain out of the european union.

what was he like? - smart, says wylie. - interesting. really interested in ideas. he‚Äôs the only straight man i‚Äôve ever talked to about intersectional feminist theory. he saw its relevance straightaway to the oppressions that conservative, young white men feel.

wylie meeting bannon was the moment petrol was poured on a flickering flame. wylie lives for ideas. he speaks 19 to the dozen for hours at a time. he had a theory to prove. and at the time, this was a purely intellectual problem. politics was like fashion, he told bannon.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
teaching gayle rubin's 'thinking sex' in class today: an essay written 26 years ago perhaps resonates the most with the times that we are living today. i cannot help but think of professior siras today, and many of my trans-kothi-queer friends who are routinely harassed, institutionally, often implicated by the existing sexual harassment laws in place. there are two stories of violence here: one offered by you who take our sexual excess, which we have turned into our politics, as offence; and the other ours who are on the other end of the heterosexist laws in place. we are once again at the fringes when popular movements like #metoo have once again turned the public sphere all about powerful men and helpless women. when last year one of my gay friends was picked up by the police in kolkata on grounds of soliciting sex-work, none of you who say due process is useless came forward to help him to file a complaint who actually wanted to file a complaint - it is the hijras who beg on the streets, the trans and kothi activists and sex workers who fought for him, got him out, and helped him file a complaint. it was an act of unthinkable and unconditional love, most gay boys i know would never have done this or show such resistance. it is a telling moment that we are living in, and i sincerely hope that all woke folks go and read rubin's essay.
*
*

text:
footage of nigel farage swigging a pint and thanking steve bannon and breitbart for the brexit result was deleted from a breitbart youtube channel, following the data scandal surrounding cambridge analytica.
.
- well done bannon, well done breitbart, the ex-ukip leader announces in the short clip. - you helped with this. hugely.

farage‚Äôs nod to steve bannon certainly hasn‚Äôt aged well in the context of the recent storm around cambridge analytica‚Äôs influence over the eu referendum.

it was revealed that data from 50 million facebook profiles were looked at against the electoral register, and then used to build an algorithm which analyses people‚Äôs personality traits in relation to their voting behaviour.

this data could then be used to find potential swing voters and create messages tailored to influence them politically.

the firm‚Äôs vice president at the time was steve bannon, who was also head of the right-wing website breitbart and was running donald trump‚Äôs campaign to become us president.

anna o'donohue
inews

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby," said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
a number of recent surveys have pointed out a #metoo movement backlash,  but new findings suggest, "even before #metoo, executives picked same-gender proteges"

for those worried that the #metoo movement has discouraged men from nurturing women‚Äôs ambitions at work, the center for talent innovation has some news: there wasn‚Äôt a lot of progress to roll back in the first place.

research released today shows that, as of a year ago, most executives, male or female, chose proteges like themselves. about 71 percent said they‚Äôve invested in more junior people of the same gender and race, according to research released today by cti, a new york-based non-profit that advises companies on diversity. sponsors also said that only about 23 percent of their pupils had a different management style or skills, according to the january 2018 poll of more than 3,200 men and women in white-collar jobs. 
we want women to know that the #metoo movement has not slowed down the progress of gender pay equality. 
anyone that tells you to "play it safe" and "don't rock the boat" is speaking out of fear.  we are here to tell every woman today, you must 
speak your truth, 
your voice matters, 
today more than ever. 
and most importantly, it's working.  since the #metoo movement, there have been massive changes on the state (35 new laws in california) and federal levels (the eeoc has classified metoo as strategic). don't stop now.  we are just getting started.

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
the gillette ad is great. i don't understand, i'm actually totally baffled, as to why men are so insistent on defending behaviours that are so clearly inconsiderate and grossly negligent of other humans. or why they find it so offensive to address that those behaviours are out there, refusing to acknowledge that they've witnessed or even done it. there's no blame here, society isn't calling all men scumbags. it's saying, hey!
there's this thing that's been normalised under this weird notion of 'masculinity' and we should probs stop that now. if you could help us with that because you are also humans that'd be great..... anyone feel free to explain why that's so troubling for so many boys? 
@thepiersmorgan perhaps you could explain why we should let boys continue to be boys in the way this ad suggests some boys are?
‚Ä¢
‚Ä¢

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby," said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
the entire controversy surrounding the misogynistic comments of hardik pandya and kl rahul during their appearance at the ‚Äúkoffee with karan‚Äù chat show is nothing but a huge pr disaster for the bcci and indian cricket.

though the board and the team management have already distanced themselves from the sexist remarks both pandya and rahul made on that show, the mega storm triggered due to those comments is bound to affect the overall image of the indian dressing room. ... cricket is not just a game in india. it‚Äôs a religion, if not more. millions look up to the national players as their role models. the aspiring youngsters, look to follow their success path, emulate them in every way.

hence, the hounour of representing india at the highest level comes with a certain responsibilities.

in this era of social media each and every move of a cricketer draws huge public attention both on and off the field. so, it is high time for the bcci, to take proper steps to educate its players as well as the support staff about the importance of maintaining proper etiquette even when they are not on the field.

sandipan banerjee writes in thecitizen.in

text:
#metoo
metoo movement started and burst all social media sites with stories of harassment and sexual abusing. harassment is real, it happens all over the world but it doesn't mean that in every #metoo story, only a male is at fault.
this movement started with an aim to help out  women and girls all around the world who are sexually abused and don't have enough courage to speak out. and this was helpful for many females to stand up for their rights and to understand what is harassment.
but now this movement has also became an opportunity for the individuals who are looking to fulfill their personal agendas or to become popular. 
many of you will disagree with me but if 90% of men who are wrong then there are 10% men in this world who give proper respect to females which they deserve.
i am not saying that only women are using this movement to hurt other men but in some situations there are men who wants to defame or hurt the reputation of other men and use this movement with wrong intentions and sometimes with the help of a female. 
this type of situation demands wide and clear judgments and neutral people to judge such situation. so that justice can be prevailed in this society. 
believe me nothing is more hurtful and wrong than when someone is accused or guilty of something he or she could never even think of doing that. i am telling this based on my experience. 
i will share my story in my next blog how i was wrongfully accused of something i could not imagine to do. so stay tuned. üå∏üå∏
.

text:
a bit more of my oxford chronicles. this is st.frideswide - the saint patron of oxford; her shrine is in the oldest part of christ church cathedral. her story is a #metoo variation of the vii c.: she was a daughter of a local king when a guy called algar, prince of leicester sought her hand in marriage. but she already was on the path of religious  life, having established the very first nunnery for herself and 12 other noble young ladies, so she rejected his advances. she, most probably, was a beautiful strong-willed girl, so algar became more desperate and sieged the city of oxford. frideswide had to flee to a forest where she performed some miracles. long story short: algar got killed, the nunnery was formed, and much later frideswide was canonised. so, a nunnery i recon was sadly a medieval answer to a career-vs-motherhood dilemma with which nowadays some young women struggle. in other photoes: edward burne-jones stained glass with the life of frideswide; alice in wonderland memorabilia in the cathedral gift shop and the great hall of the college where students have their meal.

tweet_full:
a bit more of my oxford chronicles. this is st.frideswide - the saint patron of oxford; her shrine is in the oldest part of christ church cathedral. her story is a #metoo variation of the vii c.: she was a daughter of a local king when a guy called algar, prince of leicester sought her hand in marriage. but she already was on the path of religious  life, having established the very first nunnery for herself and 12 other noble young ladies, so she rejected his advances. she, most probably, was a beautiful strong-willed girl, so algar became more desperate and sieged the city of oxford. frideswide had to flee to a forest where she performed some miracles. long story short: algar got killed, the nunnery was formed, and much later frideswide was canonised. so, a nunnery i recon was sadly a medieval answer to a career-vs-motherhood dilemma with which nowadays some young women struggle. in other photoes: edward burne-jones stained glass with the life of frideswide; alice in wonderland memorabilia in the cathedral gift shop and the great hall of the college where students have their meal.

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august 2017 and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? 'j-c' church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt, with the goonsquad known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagate‚Ñ¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are useless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is no way that gop isn't aware of this - after all, cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got as cambridge analytica. pedofiles - i bet - but the way things are bundled sure makes goebbels shiver.

trump plays along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still - the republicans willingly piggybacked this before the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
a history of trauma is a huge contributor to the development of borderline personality disorder in men and women. 
when i was 10, i was sexually abused by my uncle. this is something i‚Äôve been to afraid to talk about. something i‚Äôve been embarrassed by. everyone claimed he was just ‚Äúan affectionate guy‚Äù, well that night he showed his affections towards me. that day ruined my life. for the next 14 years i would have become untrusting, unconfident, body dysmorphic, depressed, and alone. i found it incredibly hard to date anyone, to feel affection, and to be touched. that part of my life i try and forget about, it broke me, and it broke my family. 
i‚Äôm tired of being ashamed of what made me the person i am today. because of that night, i‚Äôve learned and adapted to so many hardships in my life. i‚Äôve learned so much about myself. i think it‚Äôs important for those who are abused to come forward, as hard as it may be. and to understand that the cause of their problem can sometimes be attributed to more. 
borderline has taught me a lot about myself, and being diagnosed has lead me to further understand why i am the way i am.

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby," said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby," said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

„Éª„Éª„Éª
love letter monday: breaking cycles, breaking news

this photo was taken a month after my ex-husband and i separated. it was while i was inside that toxic marriage that i began to write. essay upon essay‚Äîchapters, perhaps‚Äîsent by my inner voice to warn me, protect me, wizen me. to let me know that contrary to his words, i did have value. that contrary to the world‚Äôs wounds, i did deserve kindness and respect. that contrary to the narrative of systemic racism and sexism that i had been born into, i had the power to author a new story. for myself. my family. my future children.

i‚Äôm thrilled to share that today, january 14, 2019, the north clackamas school district received an innovation grant from the oregon department of education to adopt i am yours into their english language arts curriculum. i am yours will be used as the common reading for high school juniors and seniors to engage in critical conversations about diversity, marginalization, social justice, racism, sexism, opportunity gap, privilege, breaking free and healing from trauma, the #metoo movement and our path forward, and how to use the power of their voices as agents of positive change, courage, and love in the world. the curriculum will be put into action in the 2019-2020 school year throughout oregon.

to you, who may be inside your moment of uncertainty, pain, or loss: have faith. you were born to experience and voice a specific story. traverse the valleys and falls of your life, pay attention to the wisdom mined from your wounds. everything can be used to inform and enrich your service to others. it will make sense. if not in the valley of pain, then one day, months, years later.

the thing that got me through that marriage was the audacious conviction that there was no way he was my story. i kept telling myself, i was born for a destiny so much bigger than the cramped quarters of a toxic home.

you and your voice matter. you were born for greatness and you embody tremendous resilience, by virtue of being human. voice your anthem. i am listening.

love, reema

love letter monday: breaking cycles, breaking news

this photo was taken a month after my ex-husband and i separated. it was while i was inside that toxic marriage that i began to write. essay upon essay‚Äîchapters, perhaps‚Äîsent by my inner voice to warn me, protect me, wizen me. to let me know that contrary to his words, i did have value. that contrary to the world‚Äôs wounds, i did deserve kindness and respect. that contrary to the narrative of systemic racism and sexism that i had been born into, i had the power to author a new story. for myself. my family. my future children.

i‚Äôm thrilled to share that today, january 14, 2019, the noh clackamas school district received an innovation grant from the oregon depament of education to adopt i am yours into their english language as curriculum. i am yours will be used as the common reading for high school juniors and seniors to engage in critical conversations about diversity, marginalization, social justice, racism, sexism, oppounity gap, privilege, breaking free and healing from trauma, the  movement and our path forward, and how to use the power of their voices as agents of positive change, courage, and love in the world. the curriculum will be put into action in the 2019-2020 school year throughout oregon.

to you, who may be inside your moment of unceainty, pain, or loss: have faith. you were born to experience and voice a specific story. traverse the valleys and falls of your life, pay attention to the wisdom mined from your wounds. everything can be used to inform and enrich your service to others. it will make sense. if not in the valley of pain, then one day, months, years later.

the thing that got me through that marriage was the audacious conviction that there was no way he was my story. i kept telling myself, i was born for a destiny so much bigger than the cramped quaers of a toxic home.

you and your voice matter. you were born for greatness and you embody tremendous resilience, by viue of being human. voice your anthem. i am listening.

love, reema

text:
widows | lynda la plante

this book was a spur of the moment purchase, i was wandering around whitcoulls (nz based book/magazine/toy store) struggling to find something i wanted to read on holiday. as i was walking out i spotted the cover sitting on a table of the latest releases. widows isn‚Äôt a new release, but this edition is. it was re-released to coincide with the movie that hit cinemas in 2018. widows is written by lynda la plante, a mainstay of the crime/thriller genre and by all accounts a very successful writer and former actress.

widows is a heist thriller set in 80‚Äôs london (my favourite city). i loved reading about locations i‚Äôve visited, plus it made it so much easier to envisage parts of the story. three women are left widowed after a security van robbery goes awry. battling through her grief, dolly rawlins locates her late husbands ledgers with its pages overflowing with plans for the disastrous heist. teaming up with the two other widows and a latecomer, they begin to formulate a plan.

it took me a while to really get into this, it started off a little too slowly for my liking but it definitely picked up the pace towards the middle ending in an exciting climax. i took longer than usual to finish it as well, i think i just had different expectations. however, please don‚Äôt think this is a lousy book, it‚Äôs merely my opinion as la plante is an excellent writer. 
the characters were developed well and i really liked all of them, little bits about each one were unveiled as the story went on. their personalities grew much like they would in real life when faced with adverse conditions, quite realistic. shirley sounds like a great gal and i imagine would be fun to hang around if she were real! i should add that his was written more than 30 years ago but has aged like a fine wine, the women‚Äôs issues are still relevant and quite timely given the #metoo movement. 
all in all, this did wind up to be an enjoyable read, i would recommend it to others who are after a thriller that is female centric (finally!) and not too heavy on the violence. the second in the series, widows‚Äô revenge is due to be realised next month so i‚Äôll definitely be picking that up.

7! the average life span of a trafficking victim is reported to be 7 years. the listed causes of death are attack, abuse, hiv and other std's, malnutrition, overdose or suicide. 
with this in mind, ending the commercial sexual exploitation of children is truly a matter of life and death. likewise, prevention and awareness education can also help people to recognize the signs of someone who is being trafficked, which will ultimately lead to lives being saved as well. please don't turn a blind eye. if you see something, say something. 
if you are a victim or suspect that a child may be a victim of human trafficking, please call 911 or call the national human trafficking resource center at 1-888-373-7888 for help. all victims of slavery and human trafficking have rights and are protected by international, federal, and state law.

text: ‚óºÔ∏èbacklash‚óºÔ∏èproctor & gamble is urging men to shave their ‚Äútoxic masculinity‚Äù in a new ad for gillette @gillette razors. the ad shows men fighting, cooking barbecue, and verbally harassing women, interspersed with news reports about the #metoo movement. a new ad from p&g razor brand gillette encourages men to reexamine themselves and the way that they raise young boys. the ad, which is called ‚Äúwe believe: the best men can be,‚Äù is essentially a two-minute broad generalization about the way that men act and think. the ad depicts men getting into fights, standing in front of barbecue grills, and verbally harassing women. the ad also heavily features news clips discussing the recent #metoo movement. in a comment to the wall street journal, pankaj bhalla, gillette‚Äôs brand director, said that the advertisement is a meditation on the changes that men must make in america. ‚Äúthis is an important conversation happening, and as a company that encourages men to be their best, we feel compelled to both address it and take action of our own,‚Äù bhalla said. ‚Äúwe are taking a realistic look at what‚Äôs happening today, and aiming to inspire change by acknowledging that the old saying ‚Äòboys will be boys‚Äô is not an excuse. we want to hold ourselves to a higher standard, and hope all the men we serve will come along on that journey to find our ‚Äòbest‚Äô together.‚Äù the ad immediately turned off customers, many of which said that they are done buying gillette @gillette products. ‚Äúi am taking action,‚Äù one twitter user said in response to gillette‚Äôs call for action. ‚Äúi‚Äôm researching every product made by proctor & gamble, throwing any i have in the trash, and never buying any of them again until everyone involved in this ad from top to bottom is fired and the company issues a public apology.‚Äù

text:
everyday i ask myself, ‚Äúare you ready?‚Äù i answer, ‚Äúyes i am.‚Äù i say to myself, ‚Äúwalk on.‚Äù i spend the day in motion. 
everyday i try to do something on this long walk, the walk that will take me to the end of my days. 
some days i think to myself, "what does it mean to be alive if we don‚Äôt educate ourselves; our raw, true selves?" i wonder, "am i here to find love? self love? balance? spirituality? or just to walk in circles, listening to what the news says is good and bad?" the only thing in life that keeps one alive is the ability to learn; to have an opinion, and to share knowledge. so read, read, and read! google it! talk about it and welcome our ideas! for these are the very reasons why we share what we share... #metoo #fightback #art  #photography #sydneyproduction #internationalscreenacademy

text: we often tell ourselves contingencies of when we will matter, when we will be of value, when we will be worthy.  these are falsehoods.  we are worthy today, right now, just as we are, in this moment.  our worthiness does not depend on the number on the scale or the size of our clothing, what position we hold at work or if we got that promotion, if we struggle with mental illness, or if we attended college.  we - you - are worthy right this very minute.  as you are.  no prerequisites üíú

what if you take the wrong one? what law is there that says you can‚Äôt turn back & switch paths again? sometimes a road makes a full circle and tries to put itself back into your path-because their road got washed out! not because you are extremely special in their eyes, or because you are their dream or the love they can‚Äôt live  without! lies, all lies from the devil üëø 
then you remember, as the light shines in through the darkness, how that road made you feel, how low you felt, how you had no self esteem, respect, dignity or love for your own soul, and the loneliness that came with that road.....instead of shriveling up in fear, stand tall like the strength you are,  and run down a side dirt road , that has always been there waiting for you to make that u-turn! dirt is gold, when gold is coal!

text: #guardianbooks pat barker‚Äôs brilliant story of the final stages of the trojan war is a devastating account told from the perspective of the trojan women captured as ‚Äúbooty‚Äù (mainly as sex slaves) by the greeks. it fills these gaps in homer‚Äôs iliad, which is told purely from the male warriors‚Äô point of view. barker captures the complexities of the women‚Äôs situation, as well as of the famous love between achilles and patroclus - in this regard, barker does far better than madeline miller‚Äôs ‚Äúsong of achilles‚Äù. so many of the issues raised resonate with the #metoo movement - from women‚Äôs bodies being seen as chattels for men‚Äôs pleasure to the efforts to silence women‚Äôs voices on all manner of issues. a novel of ancient times for our time.

text:
¬´ r a n t ¬ª
.
.
.
i've met people. i've lived with people. that doesn't mean i know them that well. all of us hide secrets, whilst laughing along the rhythm. there are only few who get close to our hearts, when it feels safe in their presence. when you're completely comfortable with what is happening. but when you don't, what do you do? i looked for a reason to leave, even though it was staring right in front of me. they tried to give all of them to me, when i wasn't ready to do myself. i didn't want to be someone who listens quietly and let the pain overpower. i had to rip the bandage one way or another. it would hurt, i know. but it would only be for a second and then it will be gone... like they will, once out of my life. like all the stories of the past i've kept safe until now... if you have no reason to stay, it's a good reason to go. .
.
// ayesha fatimah

text:
gillette's latest ad expands their popular tagline "the best a man can get" to "the best a man can be". the controversial ad titled "we believe" tackles issues like bullying, toxic masculinity, sexual harassment and lends its voice to the #metoo movement. it has gotten almost 3 million views on youtube currently and many people against the movement have openly expressed plans to boycott the brand for not being a masculine brand and stating that the ad has a "feminist propaganda" starting hashtags like "boycott gillette" and "go woke go broke".
gillette also launched thebestmencanbe.org and pledged $1million per year for 3 years to provide role models for men and the building a better man project.

gillette president, gary coombe says "for us, the decision to publicly assert our beliefs while celebrating men who are doing things right was an easy choice that makes a difference." we commend gillette for using their brand to speak on issues that affect all of us and hope more brands can use their influential voices positively. these conversations need to be had.

watch parts of the video and share your thoughts with us in the comment section. to watch the full video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kopmueyp3a0

long live men who know what it is to be a man! üí™üèª‚ù§Ô∏èüëäüèª .

text:
i often wish i was some sort of superhero or had some super powers! i wish i could fight villains and protect people! but then i realise that superheroes aren‚Äôt real! iron man isn‚Äôt real! spider-man isn‚Äôt real! but i am real! i fight my own bunch of villains! i fight those destructive thoughts! i fall and rise up again... just like those superheroes! i don‚Äôt wear a cape or have awesome powers, but heck, i do have some effing strength to go through all the hardships life has sent me!! i have amazing powers like this one called generosity!!! or that one that always lets me see the good in people no matter what! i am a superhero... in a way! üòÇ i often wonder why life sent me those hardships.. because believe me, i wish i had never gone through anything related to sexual assaults... but i see and understand that i don‚Äôt choose my battles. they come and i have to face them!!! at the end of every journey, i earn a new power!!! compassion, forgiveness, mercy, patience.. and so much more! i never lose!!! i always win!! i am my own superhero! i save people with words and support! i learn how to be stronger every day! it‚Äôs not an easy life, but i‚Äôve accepted it and even though i wish this was the last battle, i know that it‚Äôs only the beginning and that life isn‚Äôt done with me yet. so let all the villains come and fight me! i‚Äôll fall, cry and dream of giving up, but i‚Äôm never alone... i will stand on my feet again and again and again until my last breath. i‚Äôm ester... an ordinary human who‚Äôs accepted life as it is.
.
.

text: not that long ago @matt_and_nat_  had a "what's in your bag" contest for their followers and there was just something about it that stuck with me. i'm not an anthropologist but the results were fascinating. i thought how that's an amazing way to get to know something about a person so here we are. if you're interested to see what's in this animal loving city dwellers bag, then by all means, keep reading. top right to left: 1) dog leash + dog collar - i remember the first time i found a dog, i was going to pick up my partner from work and next to his office there was an extremely friendly german shepard, lucky there were other people around that held him till i ran to a pet store to get a leash. city hall workers (now known as green police) came and took him and returned him to his owner before i managed to come back, so since then they are a must items in my bag. 2) fiorelli wallet. 3) pepper spray - because #metoo but also too late. whoever you are, reading this now you should know that today is a perfect day to think about femmes in you life and how you can enable them to protect them selves in the future. 4) keys on a string - cause it's so helpful when you have your hands full or you wanna get in asap in order to avoid a neighbour. 5) dog treat - to tempt them if lost and not that people trusting. 6) hard candy. #vegan of course. 7) kleenex. 8) mix of various pills. 9) melem - best thing that happened to lips - ever. 10) pouches of wet food - for the street cats that don't like it dry or just to treat them but mostly it serves me as a back up for when i've already passed away the dry food. 11) reusable bag - please, get it for yourself and everyone you know! 12) bird food - mix of seeds and grains - keeps birds away from cat food which keeps them safe from cats/harm. this is also my newest "must always carry with me" addition. 13) dry cat food - cause there's #cats everywhere. /// i really wanna ask "so, what's in your bag" but then a story about a murderer that carries a severed human head in his bag starts to unravel. :x  #toomuchcrime by. üôã

12) bird food - mix of seeds and grains - keeps birds away from cat food which keeps them safe from cats/harm. this is also my newest "must always carry with me" addition. 13) dry cat food - cause there's #cats everywhere. /// i really wanna ask "so, what's in your bag" but then a story about a murderer that carries a severed human head in his bag starts to unravel. :x  #toomuchcrime by. üôã

text: light rises when darkness fades, curled in like a cat, one eye sleepily open waiting for a knowing to appear. tears and tears and tears will sense the moment of doneness, the last droplet entwined with an aching promise of hope. this is on the edge of understanding, the rest of the brain consumed by long-gone pain never witnessed...never said...never heard. a series of no-no-no's and grandma-please-help-me's dangle alongside screams until the echos whip savagely on a circling in-side wind. the sound is avoided, and oddly, also embraced as this long night rages on, tears spear the wind, gathering each lost utterance in unfamiliar comfort...a stab into the darkness; no-one knowing if it will ever come to matter at all.
