text:
so first @johnniewalkerus decides go political left and now @gillette (see recent post on their page). i enjoyed way back when companies would tell me what they are about, their culture and belief system, and left it at that. johnnie walker launched their jane walker with some mixed message about supporting women but do state they they are placing their support behind the 2019 women's march on dc. and most recently gillette throws their hat into the political arena with this attempt to throw their support behind #metoo while throwing shade on toxic masculinity. before long i can only assume that @charmin will announce their campaign for butthole equality.
.
it's not that i'm anti-woman or wish to get into the age old argument over gender inequality. what i do wish to point out is the further you publicize an issue and the harsher you go demonize it the greater the pendulum swing the opposite direction. i see it in parts of town, in my children's school, and most recently a male who was at my daughter's friend's birthday party. instead of demonizing men or going overload on women why don't we just discuss values and respect? well, it would make more sense but it wouldn't sell. middle of the road common sense never sells. so unfortunately i as a father now need to correct the bullshit the schools put in their minds and get to have arguements with flaming representatives of the "beta male" movement who seem to enjoy calling me a chauvinist bully.
.
to wrap this one up i will offer this perspective...
men and women aren't equal. if we were there would be only one sex, not two. men as a whole can do things women can't and women as a whole can do things men can't, some is genetic and some social. this is an extremely broad statement i know. instead of this overreaction of equality why can't we instead discuss commonality while celebrating the differences?
.
just my two cents on the matter though. sharing it so i can get it out of my head and get back to work. 
#strengthpunishes

text: there is no true change without backlash. change is hard because people overestimate the value of what they have‚Äîand underestimate the value of what they may gain by giving that up. unless you are prepared to give up something valuable you will never be able to truly change at all, because you'll be forever in the control of things you can't give up. some times it‚Äôs obvious that change needs to occur - since i have a potty trainer right now, an easy example is a messy diaper needs to be changed right now or the baby will be left with horrific diaper rash (which i have had to care for after a neglectful parent left his daughter in a messy diaper screaming for hours). then there is change that needs to occur because something has slowly occurred - like for me, toxic relationships and toxic choices, working in a corporate office with rich white males with multiple houses telling me to work harder so they could get richer - smiling on the outside while i was dying on the inside. extreme changes had to occur as the results of my choices over several years resulted in crashing head first into a wall - why is every partner i am talking to or dating a narcissist and liar and cheater - i was finally forced to face that head on and look inside for the change that had to occur to stop the cycle. give up everything that felt comfortable - drinking, a cushy - soul killing job, and toxic people who didn‚Äôt care about me truly. on a bigger scale, our societal blind eye to the small behaviors and little slips and slides along the way; the fear to look inside and make the individual change - but now, as a society, we have also hit the wall, and the fake smile isn‚Äôt going to work anymore. if you‚Äôre raising mini men like me, i strongly suggest you to check out ‚Äúthe mask we live in‚Äù on netflix - it changed my entire outlook on parenting mini men, culture and raising men today. we should all hold ourselves accountable to stop turning a blind eye - and to stop smiling on the outside while we are dying on the inside. we are supposed to live during this life not just slowly die. love this #gillette. #themasktheylivein #metoo #bullying #raisingmen #change #accountability #live

text:
i‚Äôve taught on sex and sexuality for many years. i‚Äôve watched people treat it recklessly, i‚Äôve been sexually assaulted several times, i‚Äôve lived, i‚Äôve made errors in judgement. i learned many lessons. i‚Äôm saddened by how so many women give away a part of themselves in need for love and acceptance, and for some, it‚Äôs taken from them - a rape of the soul. my work has transitioned. perhaps it‚Äôs because of what i‚Äôve learned and lived. regardless, it‚Äôs all part of what has been written in the scribes. lies may be told, to others, yet the ones that penetrate deepest are the ones we tell and hold onto within ourselves. to live as a leader is to be a leader. this is not forced, for to do so would only be to emulate force. force is force. 
allow these words to penetrate. 
educate. rise. choose wisely. 
be the woman you‚Äôre proud to show to the world. ~alisa k

text:
according to the survey of inmates of state correctional facilities by the u.s. department of justice bureau of justice statistics. * those inmates who were convicted of committing violent acts against children were more like to have been white, a percentage of nearly 70%, than any other race. * white inmates were nearly three times more likely to have victimized a child than black inmates. ‚¨áÔ∏è
according to rainn (rape, abuse and incest national network) and the bureau of justice, 57% of all sexual violence perpetrators are white males.
‚¨áÔ∏è
according to suicide prevention expert, dr. christine moutier, white, middle-aged men account for 70% of deaths from suicide each year.¬†nine-tenths of them¬†are from a lower socioeconomic classthese are being called¬†‚Äúdeaths of despair.‚Äùharvard public policy professor robert d. putnam, told the bbc, "this is part of the larger emerging pattern of evidence of the links between poverty, hopelessness and health.‚Äù veterans are often one of the largest segments within this group. according to a 2014¬†veterans affairs¬†(va) report, 20 commit suicide each day. 65% of them are age 50 or older. a larger segment of this group has chosen the slow suicid

according to scientists, any two average white people will have less than 1% the genetic diversity of any two average black people. this gives evidence to a long held academic theory: white people are the result of inbreeding among a tribe of indo-euro

what white people don't want you to know." gene pool of average european severely depleted.. if your heritage is non-african, you are part neanderthal, according to a new study in the july issue of molecular biological magazine.
üëá
neanderthal inbreeding has left humans weaker: non-africans have lower fitness levels due to 'genetic burden'.
genetic analysis has revealed that mutations built up in neanderthals.

according to the survey of inmates of state correctional facilities by the u.s. department of justice bureau of justice statistics. * those inmates who were convicted of committing violent acts against children were more like to have been white, a percentage of nearly 70%, than any other race. * white inmates were nearly three times more likely to have victimized a child than black inmates. ‚¨áÔ∏è
according to rainn (rape, abuse and incest national network) and the bureau of justice, 57% of all sexual violence perpetrators are white males.

according to scientists, any two average white people will have less than 1% the genetic diversity of any two average black people. this gives evidence to a long held academic theory: white people are the result of inbreeding among a tribe of indo-euro

what white people don't want you to know." gene pool of average european severely depleted.. if your heritage is non-african, you are part neanderthal, according to a new study in the july issue of molecular biological magazine.
üëá
neanderthal inbreeding has left humans weaker: non-africans have lower fitness levels due to 'genetic burden'.
genetic analysis has revealed that mutations built up in neanderthals.

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
thoughts?

one of the manliest brands in men's products has hit on an unusual strategy for divided times: questioning "#toxicmasculinity." #gillette, the procter & gamble co. brand that for three decades has used the tagline, "the best a man can get," is building a new campaign around the #metoo movement, a risky approach that will be the latest test of how successfully big consumer brands can navigate tricky social movements. 
the ad, created by the brand's ad agency grey and titled "we believe," opens with audio of news about the #metoo movement, bullying and "toxic masculinity." a narrator goes on to dispute the notion that "boys will be boys," asking, "is this the best a man can get? is it? we can't hide from it. it has been going on far too long. we can't laugh it off, making the same old excuses." "this is an important conversation happening, and as a company that encourages men to be their best, we feel compelled to both address it and take action of our own," said pankaj bhalla, gillette brand director for #northamerica, in an emailed statement. "we are taking a realistic look at what's happening today, and aiming to inspire change by acknowledging that the old saying '#boyswillbeboys' is not an excuse." but in a sign of the risks gillette is taking, the ad quickly provoked passionate rebukes online. "the video is sad and depressing while putting all men in a bad light," one twitter user wrote. "men aren't just waking up to bad things that are going on. there have always been good men. bad ones too, yes, but the same can be said about women." the new gillette ad was meant to inspire positive behavior but spends too much time exposing the behavior that men have been criticized for, said susan cantor, chief executive of branding firm redpeak. "men are saying, we feel marginalized, criticized and accused rather than feeling inspired empowered and encouraged." üñêüèæmore in commentsüëáüèæ#populationcontrol #socialengineering #familyrightsmovement #emasculation #feminization #betamale #depopulation #dehumanization

text:
‚Äúfor the first time ever, apa is releasing guidelines to help psychologists work with men and boys.
at first blush, this may seem unnecessary. for decades, psychology focused on men (particularly white men), to the exclusion of all others. and men still dominate professionally and politically: as of 2018, 95.2 percent of chief operating officers at fortune 500 companies were men. according to a 2017 analysis by fortune, in 16 of the top companies, 80 percent of all high-ranking executives were male. meanwhile, the 115th congress, which began in 2017, was 81 percent male.
but something is amiss for men as well. men commit 90 percent of homicides in the united states and represent 77 percent of homicide victims. they‚Äôre the demographic group most at risk of being victimized by violent crime. they are 3.5 times more likely than women to die by suicide, and their life expectancy is 4.9 years shorter than women‚Äôs. boys are far more likely to be diagnosed with attention-deficit hyperactivity disorder than girls, and they face harsher punishments in school‚Äîespecially boys of color.
apa‚Äôs new guidelines for psychological practice with boys and men strive to recognize and address these problems in boys and men while remaining sensitive to the field‚Äôs androcentric past. thirteen years in the making, they draw on more than 40 years of research showing that traditional masculinity is psychologically harmful and that socializing boys to suppress their emotions causes damage that echoes both inwardly and outwardly.‚Äù

text:
‚Ä¢ f e e l s ‚Ä¢ i‚Äôm over the highlight reel, i‚Äôm over the inauthenticity, i‚Äôm over artificial happiness. so here goes, i‚Äôm gonna keep it really real with y‚Äôall. 
whew 34, you did a number on me. hands down one of the hardest years of my life. last year i finally decided to confront my past. the past that i have been suppressing, denying, making excuses for. and for the first time in my adult life i started seeing a therapist. better late than never am i right?! and no, that has not immediately fixed things. i so wish it did but that‚Äôs not quite how it works. it has actually made my life a bit more challenging. it brought things up to the surface that i have been holding deep, deep down and has completely thrown me off balance. it‚Äôs had a detrimental effect on my relationship and my overall well being. my triggers seem amplified and at times it feels like i‚Äôve lost all control. 
this is not easy for me to admit. opening, sharing, being vulnerable scares me to death. i feel like i always have to put on a brave face, walk around with a smile, spread the love, be the light, yet sometimes all i want to do is break the fuck down. but i owe this to myself.  i would much rather work through my trauma than to overlook it, than to minimize it.

as @kcp_sav so eloquently reminded me in class last night, e v e r y t h i n g is temporary. this journey will not last forever. this too shall pass. i know i will get through this. i know i will emerge a stronger, more compassionate and enlightened being. i know i will soon get back to my normal, happy go lucky self. and yes, i need to remind myself of that over and over. so i‚Äôm dedicating my 35th year to strength; physical, emotional, mental, and unconditional love for myself. #metoo #breakthestigma #whenkeepingitrealgoeswrong

text:
2009 is the year everything went down.

my life felt like a giant dead end and i had no clue if it would ever change.

i tried to act normal. i did my best to pretend that i had it all together and was just moving along society‚Äôs timeline.

yet whenever i thought about the future, it looked dark. it scared me. i‚Äôd reach for things outside of me to escape and distract myself from reality because facing it was just too difficult.

i‚Äôd pray to god for things to get clearer yet they only seemed to get worse.

i had never meditated before. i had no idea how to enhance my intuition or access this thing called mindfulness. i bailed on countless therapists and couldn‚Äôt stick to any goal long term.

my form of self care was a bottle of wine and ben & jerry‚Äôs along with the latest netflix dvd that arrived in the mail.

i wondered if this was it. 
that all life held for me was the momentum of just getting by. settling. day in and day out.

everyone else seemed to have it figured out except me. i did my best to try to acknowledge this fate but there was a part of me deep down that felt like maybe there could be more... little did i know the turn my existence would take by the fall of that year and that life would honestly never be the same again. 
the before photo was taken a couple months before my saturn return when the universe dropped me to my knees to get on a path that would one day be my calling... and the rest is herstory.

i share the full experience on my latest episode of curiously confident, including my #metoo moment, the nature of saturn return and how i finally let myself be helped & supported.

what would i tell the girl of the past? ‚Äúyou‚Äôre beautiful. you‚Äôre so loved. you can do anything and you don‚Äôt have to feel like you don‚Äôt deserve anything better anymore.‚Äù ‚Äútake it one baby step at a time. don‚Äôt try to fall in love or even like yourself, just give yourself a chance to be slight okay with who you are. it will change, i promise.‚Äù

text:
‚†Ä
‚†Ä
how do you feel about using your partners device and how does your partner feel about using yours? ‚†Ä
letting a partner scroll through your phone or computer implies trust.‚†Ä
however there is a place for privacy in loving and trusting relationships and a request for privacy does not mean that a partner is up to no good.‚†Ä
what is your take on this?‚†Ä
‚†Ä
digital dating abuse is the use of technologies such as texting and social networking to bully, harass, stalk or intimidate a partner. often this behavior is a form of verbal or emotional abuse perpetrated online.‚†Ä
in a healthy relationship, all communication is respectful whether in person, online or by phone. it is never okay for someone to do or say anything that makes you feel bad, lowers your self-esteem or manipulates you. you may be experiencing digital abuse if your partner: steals or insists on being given your passwords or looks through your phone frequently, checks up on your pictures, texts and outgoing calls.‚†Ä
‚†Ä
you do not have to share your passwords or devices with anyone.‚†Ä
‚†Ä

text:
it‚Äôs hard to put in to words the experience of seeing your byline in the new york times. this is a watershed moment for me. 
the title is provocative. my intention is to highlight the lack of women entering my profession. this is a career that is fulfilling, you get to help people accomplish their hopes and dreams. it is financially secure, although that wasn‚Äôt always the case when everyone worked for sales commissions. and you get to live a regular life, with time for your family, friends, and non-work interests.

text:
i can't unlove you

the love letters which you crumpled and threw along with your feelings. trust me, i felt like a dustbin. my body carrying your used emotions, half  eaten trust
and your plastic promises which were crushed. but, i am glad that i was able to keep you clean.

the photo frame which you broke in anger and threw away out of the window along with my memories, trust me, i felt broken; like a glass. my body was fragmented just as your fragile character. but i am glad that i distant myself from you and was able to respect your needs.

the shirt which i gave you, you left it deserted in your closet along with my presence. trust me, i felt ignored. my body was lonely as if the soul had departed with your care. but, i am glad i was able to free you from the cage of my selfless love.

i plead for your presence forever but l was glad that reality made a hijack over my illusions.

dear,
you hurt me, leave me alone, play with me, or even piss me off.

i am sure,
i can't love you.
and

i can't unlove either.

darshan sanghvi.
(@darshansanghvi28)
.
.
.
.

text:
thoughts?

one of the manliest brands in men's products has hit on an unusual strategy for divided times: questioning "#toxicmasculinity." #gillette, the procter & gamble co. brand that for three decades has used the tagline, "the best a man can get," is building a new campaign around the #metoo movement, a risky approach that will be the latest test of how successfully big consumer brands can navigate tricky social movements. 
the ad, created by the brand's ad agency grey and titled "we believe," opens with audio of news about the #metoo movement, bullying and "toxic masculinity." a narrator goes on to dispute the notion that "boys will be boys," asking, "is this the best a man can get? is it? we can't hide from it. it has been going on far too long. we can't laugh it off, making the same old excuses." "this is an important conversation happening, and as a company that encourages men to be their best, we feel compelled to both address it and take action of our own," said pankaj bhalla, gillette brand director for #northamerica, in an emailed statement. "we are taking a realistic look at what's happening today, and aiming to inspire change by acknowledging that the old saying '#boyswillbeboys' is not an excuse." but in a sign of the risks gillette is taking, the ad quickly provoked passionate rebukes online. "the video is sad and depressing while putting all men in a bad light," one twitter user wrote. "men aren't just waking up to bad things that are going on. there have always been good men. bad ones too, yes, but the same can be said about women." the new gillette ad was meant to inspire positive behavior but spends too much time exposing the behavior that men have been criticized for, said susan cantor, chief executive of branding firm redpeak. "men are saying, we feel marginalized, criticized and accused rather than feeling inspired empowered and encouraged." üñêüèæmore in commentsüëáüèæ#populationcontrol #socialengineering #familyrightsmovement #emasculation #feminization #betamale #depopulation #dehumanization

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking ‚Äòugh. totally ugly‚Äô to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think it‚Äôs worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people don‚Äôt necessarily know it‚Äôs being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so it‚Äôs worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that you‚Äôre doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of people‚Äôs personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldn‚Äôt have seen, and couldn‚Äôt have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, ‚Äúwould work for anyone‚Äù. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean they‚Äôre mercenaries. they‚Äôll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

it‚Äôs an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing ‚Äì at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public ‚Äì our intimate family connections, our ‚Äúlikes‚Äù, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole that‚Äôs expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
everyone‚Äôs showing off their first profile photos on fb and comparing to now and i‚Äôm over here comparing my ‚Äúnot really‚Äù twin boys and my health goal on the right!  the girl on the right had just turned 23 and had a 18 month old (sorry b we cut you out of the photo ü§¶üèª‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏èüòÇ).
.
.
for those of you following along in my health journey, you know i was diagnosed with type 2 diabetes october 2nd. 2 days before my birthday ü§∑üèª‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è. my health journey isn‚Äôt about losing weight (that‚Äôs a huge plus) but more about controlling my eating habits so i can fight this disease without medicine and give my boys a healthier me. because let‚Äôs face it, i‚Äôm not 23 anymore and chasing after a toddler isn‚Äôt as easy as it used to be! .
.
i have been low carb. no certain diet, just making conscious efforts to limit my carbs. no more than 37 g per meal and no more than 25 g for a snack. so at the most i‚Äôm having a little over 160g a day.  that sounds like a lot until you start looking at labels. for instance, a small cookies and cream milkshake at chick fil a is 85g, that‚Äôs more than i‚Äôm allowed for 2 meals!!! and to think, i used to eat a normal sized one after a meal üò≥. i can‚Äôt go lower with my carbs and go completely keto because my body needs certain amounts of carbs to balance my glucose levels. it‚Äôs not easy, but it‚Äôs totally worth it.  and the plus, i‚Äôm down 27 lbs. and almost 4 pant sizes üò≥. .
.
if you‚Äôve set a goal for yourself make sure it‚Äôs realistic, give yourself a little wiggle room (i have a small fry every now and then with grilled chicken!), and don‚Äôt obsess over a scale! our weight fluctuates for many different reasons and we don‚Äôt want to discourage the journey!
.
.
what are your health goals this year?! i‚Äôd love to hear and if you‚Äôd check in on me, we can hold each other accountable! .
.
.
#type2diabetes #lowcarbrecipes #weightlossupport #beselective #selfcare
